      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The problem is that private equity portfolios are not only opaque, but also built on illiquid assets ‚Äî investments like restructured companies that have no transparent public valuation and cannot be easily converted into cash. To understand why this is so dangerous, let‚Äôs look to an unlikely source: a scandal across the Atlantic involving the original manuscripts of some of the world‚Äôs most famous literary works, from Andr√© Breton‚Äôs surrealist manifestos to Charlotte Bront√´‚Äôs early writings to a long-lost scroll of the Marquis de Sade.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The tale is centered on a genteel Left Bank neighborhood in central Paris, an area said to boast more antiquarian booksellers and document dealers than anywhere else on the planet. Here, in cramped, dusty shops, illuminated manuscripts, intimate letters penned by historical greats, and autographed first editions have long commanded international attention and astronomical prices.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "type": "callout",
        "calloutEmoji": "üí°",
        "calloutText": "<em>You can order a copy of </em>The Curse of the Marquis de Sade <em>from your favorite bookstore by </em><a href=\"https://www.joelwarner.com/\"><em>clicking here</em></a><em>.</em>",
        "backgroundColor": "grey"
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "But the market was small and insular, fueled by a handful of expert dealers and the fervor of a few thousand high-end clients. That changed in the early 2000s, when a local upstart investment company called ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "Aristophil",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=uOfF_XnadrM",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " began selling joint ownership shares of collections of letters and manuscripts for a few hundred euros on up. Suddenly, teachers, police officers, shopkeepers, and others making a modest living all over Europe could own a piece of the country‚Äôs celebrated literary heritage ‚Äî and earn 40 percent returns in five years, promised the independent advisors touting the operation.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "As the newspaper ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 2,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "Le Figaro",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": " declared, it was ‚Äúthe heyday of the manuscript.‚Äù At book auctions, Aristophil agents sent bids skyrocketing, fueling a bull market and drawing out texts that had long been hidden away in ch√¢teau libraries. Everybody made money ‚Äî the booksellers, the investors, and most of all, Aristophil. The company amassed one of the largest private collections of letters and manuscripts in the world ‚Äî including Napol√©on‚Äôs love notes to Josephine, Isaac Newton‚Äôs personal notebooks, and fragments of the Dead Sea Scrolls.",
