            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.lexology.com/library/detail.aspx?g=d24536c0-ea31-40e8-b3c1-0b2949ce6a1b",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ". Police raided Aristophil, seizing everything. They claimed the company was an elaborate Ponzi scheme, in which new investments were used to pay off old ones in order to make the operation appear sound as it grew ever bigger. Aristophil‚Äôs steadily rising rates of return were being driven by ever-more generous estimates provided by the company‚Äôs well-compensated document specialists. Such hefty markups were never challenged, since Aristophil functioned as a closed system. Once acquired, its books and manuscripts were never put up for sale at public auction.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "While the head of Aristophil is still awaiting trial, the company has long been liquidated. To help recoup the ‚Ç¨850 million that 18,000 shareholders had invested in the operation, France sold off Aristophil‚Äôs 135,000 holdings in a series of ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "high-profile auctions",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.collections-aristophil.com/en/presentation",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": ". While certain items fetched decent prices, the vast majority of sales revealed the company‚Äôs valuations were vastly overblown. On average, shareholders lost ninety percent of their investments. For many, this was their entire savings; one investor committed suicide. The only winners were the booksellers who‚Äôd been paid hefty fees to inflate the value of Aristophil‚Äôs holdings, since they now snatched up materials at rock-bottom prices.",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "After attending one of these auctions, where many items were left unsold or went for far less than their estimate, one witness declared he had witnessed a ‚Äúblack sale.‚Äù",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          }
        ],
        "direction": "ltr",
        "format": "",
        "indent": 0,
        "type": "paragraph",
        "version": 1
      },
      {
        "children": [
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "The rise and fall of Aristophil isn‚Äôt just a cautionary tale for those considering buying into U.S. joint-share art investment companies like Masterworks and Yieldstreet. Substitute private equity stakes for literary manuscripts, and the French disaster is a warning for millions of schoolworkers, firefighters, first responders, and other government employees ‚Äî because ",
            "type": "text",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "children": [
              {
                "detail": 0,
                "format": 0,
                "mode": "normal",
                "style": "",
                "text": "11 percen",
                "type": "text",
                "version": 1
              }
            ],
            "direction": "ltr",
            "format": "",
            "indent": 0,
            "type": "link",
            "rel": null,
            "target": null,
            "title": null,
            "url": "https://www.investmentcouncil.org/private-equity-delivers-the-strongest-returns-for-public-servants/",
            "version": 1
          },
          {
            "detail": 0,
            "format": 0,
            "mode": "normal",
            "style": "",
            "text": "t of all pension dollars are now invested in private equity assets.",
            "type": "text",
